<!-- post # 18 --><font color="#FF0000">KEEP UP THE WORK</font><br><tt>Thu Nov 14  1:39:52 US/Eastern 1996</tt><p>     I am 30 and was in the Navy for 4 1/2 years in the late 80's. I really hope that PBS or somebody can keep a site like this going! <br><br>      When I was aboard a cruiser (USS Truxtun CGN-35) in 1988, we went to the Gulf to 'keep the sea lanes open.' Basically, this meant siding with the Iraqis, since Iran had destroyed Kharg Island, Iraq's only gateway to the sea, and only way to get its oil to Japan and the like. <br>     Iraq had to ship all of its oil shipped through Kuwait, and, as I hope everybody remembers, the U.S. government had the military put American flags on Kuwaiti tankers and then escorted the tankers, filled with Iraqi oil, out the Gulf.<br>     The thing that totally disturbed me was that NOBODY on the ship seemed to talk about the massacre, by Iraqi soldiers, of at least 5,000 Kurds with nerve gas/ chemical agents in northern Iraq that occurred in March of 1988.  All you'd hear, from the guys manning the sand-bagged machine gun pits on deck down to the postal clerk or the potato peeler, was how we were &quot;fighting the ragheads.&quot;<br><br>      My response to 'witless' and others of like mind is this:<br><br>      If the consciousness of the American young soldier (or sailor, or whatever) went NOWHERE (downhill,even) in the 15 to 20 years following the Vietnam War, as it seemed to do in the above scenario, WHAT THE @#$% CAN WE DO ABOUT IT?           Younger people (Websurfers, everybody of recruitment age) must constantly be reminded of the Vietnam experience (hell) or they'll end up dropping out of college like I did, at 18 years of age and somewhat politically unaware, and dropping into an 'adventure' that may have no moral bearing whatsoever.  I sure wish a Vietnam Vet had talked to me before I joined.<br>      The lessons of Vietnam ARE FOR TODAY. Every time I see a 'U.S. out of the United Nations&quot; bumper sticker, I remember that.<br>                       <br>                     Thanks for listening, <br>                <br>                                    Dana<p><code>-- tundra@wport.com  (Dana  Eyde) </code><p>